 help support this podcast. It’s easy, just click the link below!\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Pay Pal Podcast Donation\" href=\"https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_s-xclick&amp;hosted_button_id=UXBZU59T4Z4D2\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://ny.shambhala.org/files/2011/08/paypal-donate-button-copy.png\" alt=\"paypal-donate-button copy\" width=\"214\" height=\"99\" /></a>\r\n\r\nPodcast production by <a title=\"Sonam Gray\" href=\"http://sonamgray.com/\" target=\"_blank\">sonamgray.com</a> and by David McKeel\r\n\r\nRead the article here: <a href=\"http://ny.shambhala.org/2015/01/02/buddhist-call-action-part-2-podcast-episode-no-61/\" target=\"_blank\">http://ny.shambhala.org/2015/01/02/buddhist-call-action-part-2-podcast-episode-no-61/</a>','A Buddhist Call to Action (part 2) – Podcast Episode No. 61','','inherit','closed','closed','','10602-revision-v1','','','2016-10-12 00:32:08','2016-10-12 00:32:08','',10602,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/12/10602-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10862,1,'2016-10-12 03:01:50','2016-10-12 03:01:50','','zencenter','','inherit','open','closed','','zencenter','','','2016-10-12 03:01:50','2016-10-12 03:01:50','',10640,'http://localhost/akyodo/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/zencenter.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(10863,1,'2016-10-12 03:02:11','2016-10-12 03:02:11','http://s3.amazonaws.com/BZCaudio/2013-09-28-Dharma-AngelKyodoWilliams.mp3','&quot;Lineage: Touching the Earth, Making Room for Everyone&quot; - Brooklyn Zen Center','','inherit','closed','closed','','10640-revision-v1','','','2016-10-12 03:02:11','2016-10-12 03:02:11','',10640,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/12/10640-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10864,1,'2016-10-12 06:11:06','2016-10-12 06:11:06','http://home.adelphi.edu/~BOHN/talks/Angel_Kyodo.mp3','&quot;love and justice are not two: diversity & inclusion in sanghas&quot; - Rock Blossom Sangha','','inherit','closed','closed','','10638-revision-v1','','','2016-10-12 06:11:06','2016-10-12 06:11:06','',10638,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/12/10638-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10874,1,'2016-10-13 00:56:36','2016-10-13 00:56:36','<a class=\"post-top-image\" href=\"/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/aKw_dharma.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-10442 size-medium\" src=\"http://angelkyodowilliams.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/aKw_dharma-223x300.jpg\" alt=\"akw_dharma\" width=\"223\" height=\"300\" /></a><em> By Garrison Institute</em>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As part of our “Garrison Talks at the JCC” event series, teachers and authors Sharon Salzberg and Rev. angel Kyodo williams recently discussed ways to bridge spiritual practice and social activism. Some of the key questions explored:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Does spiritual practice require that we love everyone?</li>\r\n 	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Does being happy mean that we avoid conflict?</li>\r\n 	<li>How can we speak differently about spiritual practice and social justice so that we honor both where we are now and where we want to go?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','Bridging Spirituality and Activism','Does spiritual practice require that we love everyone?\r\nDoes being happy mean that we avoid conflict?\r\nHow can we speak differently about spiritual practice and social justice so that we honor both where we are now and where we want to go?\r\n\r\nAs part of our “Garrison Talks at the JCC” event series, teachers and authors Sharon Salzberg and Rev. angel Kyodo williams recently discussed ways to bridge spiritual practice and social activism.','inherit','closed','closed','','10642-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 00:56:36','2016-10-13 00:56:36','',10642,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10642-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10869,1,'2016-10-12 20:37:16','2016-10-12 20:37:16','[audio]http://angelkyodowilliams.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Bridging-Activism-and-Sprituality-1.mp3[/audio]\r\n<a class=\"post-top-image\" href=\"http://angelkyodowilliams.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/aKw_dharma.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-10442 size-medium\" src=\"http://angelkyodowilliams.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/aKw_dharma-223x300.jpg\" alt=\"akw_dharma\" width=\"223\" height=\"300\" /></a><em> By Garrison Institute</em>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As part of our “Garrison Talks at the JCC” event series, teachers and authors Sharon Salzberg and Rev. angel Kyodo williams recently discussed ways to bridge spiritual practice and social activism. Some of the key questions explored:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Does spiritual practice require that we love everyone?</li>\r\n 	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Does being happy mean that we avoid conflict?</li>\r\n 	<li>How can we speak differently about spiritual practice and social justice so that we honor both where we are now and where we want to go?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n','Bridging Spirituality and Activism','Does spiritual practice require that we love everyone?\r\nDoes being happy mean that we avoid conflict?\r\nHow can we speak differently about spiritual practice and social justice so that we honor both where we are now and where we want to go?\r\n\r\nAs part of our “Garrison Talks at the JCC” event series, teachers and authors Sharon Salzberg and Rev. angel Kyodo williams recently discussed ways to bridge spiritual practice and social activism.','inherit','closed','closed','','10642-revision-v1','','','2016-10-12 20:37:16','2016-10-12 20:37:16','',10642,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/12/10642-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10871,1,'2016-10-12 21:05:33','2016-10-12 21:05:33','Rev. angel Kyodo williams joins host Vincent Horn to continue the current series on ethics in a talk about race, love, and liberation. They address race and class in American capitalism, the construct of “whiteness” as a social form of ego structure, and how Buddhism provides the tools to uncover entrenched social structures and implicit bias.\r\n','Talking Race, Love, and Liberation - Buddhist Geeks','Rev. angel Kyodo williams joins host Vincent Horn to continue the current series on ethics in a talk about race, love, and liberation. They address race and class in American capitalism, the construct of “whiteness” as a social form of ego structure, and how Buddhism provides the tools to uncover entrenched social structures and implicit bias.','inherit','closed','closed','','10631-revision-v1','','','2016-10-12 21:05:33','2016-10-12 21:05:33','',10631,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/12/10631-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10870,1,'2016-10-12 21:04:51','2016-10-12 21:04:51','Rev. angel Kyodo williams joins host Vincent Horn to continue the current series on ethics in a talk about race, love, and liberation. They address race and class in American capitalism, the construct of “whiteness” as a social form of ego structure, and how Buddhism provides the tools to uncover entrenched social structures and implicit bias.\r\n[soundcloud]https://soundcloud.com/buddhistgeeks/talking-race-love-and[/soundcloud]\r\n','Talking Race, Love, and Liberation - Buddhist Geeks','Rev. angel Kyodo williams joins host Vincent Horn to continue the current series on ethics in a talk about race, love, and liberation. They address race and class in American capitalism, the construct of “whiteness” as a social form of ego structure, and how Buddhism provides the tools to uncover entrenched social structures and implicit bias.','inherit','closed','closed','','10631-revision-v1','','','2016-10-12 21:04:51','2016-10-12 21:04:51','',10631,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/12/10631-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10873,1,'2016-10-12 21:34:05','2016-10-12 21:34:05','Rev. angel Kyodo williams joins host Vincent Horn to continue the current series on ethics in a talk about race, love, and liberation. They address race and class in American capitalism, the construct of “whiteness” as a social form of ego structure, and how Buddhism provides the tools to uncover entrenched social structures and implicit bias.','Talking Race, Love, and Liberation - Buddhist Geeks','Rev. angel Kyodo williams joins host Vincent Horn to continue the current series on ethics in a talk about race, love, and liberation. They address race and class in American capitalism, the construct of “whiteness” as a social form of ego structure, and how Buddhism provides the tools to uncover entrenched social structures and implicit bias.','inherit','closed','closed','','10631-revision-v1','','','2016-10-12 21:34:05','2016-10-12 21:34:05','',10631,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/12/10631-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10872,1,'2016-10-12 21:14:24','2016-10-12 21:14:24','Rev. angel Kyodo williams joins host Vincent Horn to continue the current series on ethics in a talk about race, love, and liberation. They address race and class in American capitalism, the construct of “whiteness” as a social form of ego structure, and how Buddhism provides the tools to uncover entrenched social structures and implicit bias.\r\n\r\n[soundcloud url=\"https://api.soundcloud.com/tracks/269687480\" params=\"auto_play=false&hide_related=false&visual=true\" width=\"100%\" height=\"450\" iframe=\"true\" /]','Talking Race, Love, and Liberation - Buddhist Geeks','Rev. angel Kyodo williams joins host Vincent Horn to continue the current series on ethics in a talk about race, love, and liberation. They address race and class in American capitalism, the construct of “whiteness” as a social form of ego structure, and how Buddhism provides the tools to uncover entrenched social structures and implicit bias.','inherit','closed','closed','','10631-revision-v1','','','2016-10-12 21:14:24','2016-10-12 21:14:24','',10631,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/12/10631-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10875,1,'2016-10-13 06:25:44','2016-10-13 06:25:44','Rev. angel Kyodo williams explores what lineage can oﬀer us and what it takes away. She has been graced with the honor of soon becoming only the second Black woman recognized as a teacher in the Zen tradition. Lineage—its keeping and its transcending—is on her mind.\n\nLINK: <a href=\"https://brooklynzen.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Brooklyn Zen Center</a>','&quot;Lineage: Touching the Earth, Making Room for Everyone&quot; - Brooklyn Zen Center','Rev. angel Kyodo williams explores what lineage can oﬀer us and what it takes away. She has been graced with the honor of soon becoming only the second Black woman recognized as a teacher in the Zen tradition. Lineage—its keeping and its transcending—is on her mind.','inherit','closed','closed','','10640-autosave-v1','','','2016-10-13 06:25:44','2016-10-13 06:25:44','',10640,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10640-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10876,1,'2016-10-13 00:59:19','2016-10-13 00:59:19','','&quot;love and justice are not two: diversity & inclusion in sanghas&quot; - Rock Blossom Sangha','','inherit','closed','closed','','10638-autosave-v1','','','2016-10-13 00:59:19','2016-10-13 00:59:19','',10638,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10638-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10877,1,'2016-10-13 00:59:26','2016-10-13 00:59:26','Rev. angel Kyodo williams explores what lineage can oﬀer us and what it takes away. She has been graced with the honor of soon becoming only the second Black woman recognized as a teacher in the Zen tradition. Lineage—its keeping and its transcending—is on her mind.','&quot;Lineage: Touching the Earth, Making Room for Everyone&quot; - Brooklyn Zen Center','Rev. angel Kyodo williams explores what lineage can oﬀer us and what it takes away. She has been graced with the honor of soon becoming only the second Black woman recognized as a teacher in the Zen tradition. Lineage—its keeping and its transcending—is on her mind.','inherit','closed','closed','','10640-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 00:59:26','2016-10-13 00:59:26','',10640,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10640-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10878,1,'2016-10-13 01:09:47','2016-10-13 01:09:47','','10400485_20129740988_739_n','','inherit','open','closed','','10400485_20129740988_739_n','','','2016-10-13 01:09:47','2016-10-13 01:09:47','',10638,'http://localhost/akyodo/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/10400485_20129740988_739_n.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(10879,1,'2016-10-13 01:10:01','2016-10-13 01:10:01','','10400485_20129780988_8566_n','','inherit','open','closed','','10400485_20129780988_8566_n','','','2016-10-13 01:10:01','2016-10-13 01:10:01','',10638,'http://localhost/akyodo/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/10400485_20129780988_8566_n.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(10881,1,'2016-10-13 06:30:38','2016-10-13 06:30:38','LINK: <a href=\"https://brooklynzen.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Brooklyn Zen Center</a>','&quot;buddha meets buddha: love and justice are not two&quot; - Brooklyn Zen Center','&nbsp;','inherit','closed','closed','','10636-autosave-v1','','','2016-10-13 06:30:38','2016-10-13 06:30:38','',10636,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10636-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10889,1,'2016-10-13 03:26:54','2016-10-13 03:26:54','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Reverend angel Kyodo williams was a guest on the Good Life Project podcast.  On this episode of the Today’s guest on the podcast is author, maverick spiritual teacher, master trainer and founder of Center for Transformative Change, Reverend angel Kyodo williams. She has been bridging the worlds of personal transformation and justice since the publication of her critically-acclaimed book, <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Being-Black-Living-Fearlessness-Compass/dp/0140196307\" target=\"_blank\">Being Black: Zen and the Art of Living with Fearlessness and Grace</a>,which was hailed as “an act of love” by Pulitzer Prize winner Alice Walker and “a classic” by Buddhist teacher Jack Kornfield. Her new book, <a href=\"http://radicaldharma.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Radical Dharma</a>, explores racial injustice as a barrier to collective awakening.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ordained as a Zen priest, Rev. angel is a Sensei, the second black woman recognized as a teacher in her lineage. She is a social visionary that applies wisdom teachings and practice to social issues. She sees Transformative Social Change as the world’s next great movement. Both fierce and grounded, she is known for her unflinching willingness to both sit with and speak uncomfortable truths with love.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In This Episode, You’ll Learn:</p>\n\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n 	<li>How growing up in New York City profoundly shaped Rev. angel’s life.</li>\n 	<li>How moments to awaken are all around us, if we just open to them.</li>\n 	<li>How to move closer to a liberated life.</li>\n 	<li>How race and the consciousness movement interact with each other.</li>\n 	<li>The #1 component contributing to a full, complete life.</li>\n 	<li>The difference between grasping and aspiration.</li>\n</ul>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mentioned in This Episode:</p>\n\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\n 	<li>Connect with Rev. Angel: a<a href=\"http://angelkyodowilliams.com/\" target=\"_blank\">ngel Kyodo williams</a> | <a href=\"http://angelkyodowilliams.com/category/blog/\" target=\"_blank\">Blog</a> | <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/zenchangeangel\" target=\"_blank\">Facebook</a> | <a href=\"https://twitter.com/zenchangeangel\" target=\"_blank\">Twitter</a> | <a href=\"https://27daysofchange.com/coming-2-2/\" target=\"_blank\">27 Days of Change</a></li>\n 	<li><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Being-Black-Living-Fearlessness-Compass/dp/0140196307\" target=\"_blank\">Being Black: Zen and the Art of Living with Fearlessness and Grace</a> by angel Kyodo Williams</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"http://radicaldharma.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Radical Dharma</a></li>\n 	<li><a href=\"http://www.richardwiseman.com/Luck.shtml\" target=\"_blank\">Richard Wiseman</a></li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Zen-Mind-Beginners-Shunryu-Suzuki-ebook/dp/B00I8USOM0?ie=UTF8&amp;btkr=1&amp;ref_=dp-kindle-redirect\" target=\"_blank\">Zen Mind, Beginner’s Mind</a> by Shunryu Suzuki</li>\n</ul>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Be sure to <a href=\"http://www.goodlifeproject.com/\" target=\"_blank\">subscribe</a> to our weekly Good Life Updates and <a href=\"http://www.goodlifeproject.com/itunes\" target=\"_blank\">listen on iTunes to make sure you never miss an episode!</a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">—</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Photo credit: Christine Alicino</p>\n<strong>Listen to the interview here:</strong> <a href=\"http://www.goodlifeproject.com/rev-angel-kyodo-williams/?t=radio\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.goodlifeproject.com/rev-angel-kyodo-williams/?t=radio</a>','On Liberation, Justice and Love - Good Life Project','In This Episode, You’ll Learn: How growing up in New York City profoundly shaped Rev. angel’s life. How moments to awaken are all around us, if we just open to them.','inherit','closed','closed','','10627-autosave-v1','','','2016-10-13 03:26:54','2016-10-13 03:26:54','',10627,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10627-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10890,1,'2016-10-13 03:23:32','2016-10-13 03:23:32','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><img class=\"wp-image-10630 alignleft\" src=\"http://angelkyodowilliams.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Angel-Wordpress-768x644-300x252.png\" alt=\"angel-wordpress-768x644\" width=\"279\" height=\"234\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In This Episode, You’ll Learn:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n 	<li>How growing up in New York City profoundly shaped Rev. angel’s life.</li>\r\n 	<li>How moments to awaken are all around us, if we just open to them.</li>\r\n 	<li>How to move closer to a liberated life.</li>\r\n 	<li>How race and the consciousness movement interact with each other.</li>\r\n 	<li>The #1 component contributing to a full, complete life.</li>\r\n 	<li>The difference between grasping and aspiration.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Today’s guest on the podcast is author, maverick spiritual teacher, master trainer and founder of Center for Transformative Change, <a href=\"http://angelkyodowilliams.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Reverend angel Kyodo williams</a>. She has been bridging the worlds of personal transformation and justice since the publication of her critically-acclaimed book, <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Being-Black-Living-Fearlessness-Compass/dp/0140196307\" target=\"_blank\">Being Black: Zen and the Art of Living with Fearlessness and Grace</a>,which was hailed as “an act of love” by Pulitzer Prize winner Alice Walker and “a classic” by Buddhist teacher Jack Kornfield. Her new book, <a href=\"http://radicaldharma.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Radical Dharma</a>, explores racial injustice as a barrier to collective awakening.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ordained as a Zen priest, Rev. angel is a Sensei, the second black woman recognized as a teacher in her lineage. She is a social visionary that applies wisdom teachings and practice to social issues. She sees Transformative Social Change as the world’s next great movement. Both fierce and grounded, she is known for her unflinching willingness to both sit with and speak uncomfortable truths with love.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In This Episode, You’ll Learn:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n 	<li>How growing up in New York City profoundly shaped Rev. angel’s life.</li>\r\n 	<li>How moments to awaken are all around us, if we just open to them.</li>\r\n 	<li>How to move closer to a liberated life.</li>\r\n 	<li>How race and the consciousness movement interact with each other.</li>\r\n 	<li>The #1 component contributing to a full, complete life.</li>\r\n 	<li>The difference between grasping and aspiration.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mentioned in This Episode:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n 	<li>Connect with Rev. Angel: a<a href=\"http://angelkyodowilliams.com/\" target=\"_blank\">ngel Kyodo williams</a> | <a href=\"http://angelkyodowilliams.com/category/blog/\" target=\"_blank\">Blog</a> | <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/zenchangeangel\" target=\"_blank\">Facebook</a> | <a href=\"https://twitter.com/zenchangeangel\" target=\"_blank\">Twitter</a> | <a href=\"https://27daysofchange.com/coming-2-2/\" target=\"_blank\">27 Days of Change</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Being-Black-Living-Fearlessness-Compass/dp/0140196307\" target=\"_blank\">Being Black: Zen and the Art of Living with Fearlessness and Grace</a> by angel Kyodo Williams</li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://radicaldharma.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Radical Dharma</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://www.richardwiseman.com/Luck.shtml\" target=\"_blank\">Richard Wiseman</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Zen-Mind-Beginners-Shunryu-Suzuki-ebook/dp/B00I8USOM0?ie=UTF8&amp;btkr=1&amp;ref_=dp-kindle-redirect\" target=\"_blank\">Zen Mind, Beginner’s Mind</a> by Shunryu Suzuki</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Be sure to <a href=\"http://www.goodlifeproject.com/\" target=\"_blank\">subscribe</a> to our weekly Good Life Updates and <a href=\"http://www.goodlifeproject.com/itunes\" target=\"_blank\">listen on iTunes to make sure you never miss an episode!</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">—</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Photo credit: Christine Alicino</p>\r\n<strong>Listen to the interview here:</strong> <a href=\"http://www.goodlifeproject.com/rev-angel-kyodo-williams/?t=radio\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.goodlifeproject.com/rev-angel-kyodo-williams/?t=radio</a>','On Liberation, Justice and Love - Good Life Project','In This Episode, You’ll Learn: How growing up in New York City profoundly shaped Rev. angel’s life. How moments to awaken are all around us, if we just open to them.','inherit','closed','closed','','10627-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 03:23:32','2016-10-13 03:23:32','',10627,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10627-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10884,1,'2016-10-13 03:08:44','2016-10-13 03:08:44','As part of the 2016 Mindfulness Retreat for People of Color,  Rev. angel Kyodo williams offers a presentation and reading based on the newly published book, Radical Dharma.\n\nIn this, Rev. angel invites us into a long overdue conversation about race alongside love and liberation. As part of this conversation, Rev. angel speaks about the social construct of whiteness, while calling us back into our humanity and to be in touch with the \"thing underneath the thing.\"\n\nA few excerpts:\n\n\"...we have the greatest potential to actually pull it up at its roots. Interestingly enough, we have that opportunity through this gift of the Dharma that actually invites us to be able to look with clear seeing eyes at things that are not real...that are figments of our imagination and figments of other people\'s imaginations...Race is a grand social figment.\"\n\n\"As Dharma teachers, the way we survived the aggression and violence of a white dominant form of Dharma that was coming to us---is that we got underneath the thing. We got to the thing underneath the thing. We had to get down to who we really were. And simultaneously appreciate our teachers, our lineages, the texts as they were given but also have a fundamental trust in who we were in our basic humanity.\" \"What does Dharma become when it\'s expressed through the experience of someone who lives in a Black body.\" --Rev. angel Kyodo williams Let us now stop, listen deeply and contemplate these teachings and sharings to cultivate our individual and collective liberation and great aspiration to strengthen the Beloved Community. To stay connected with Rev. angel, visit angelkyodowilliams.com.','Deer Park Dharmacast','\"What does Dharma become when it\'s expressed through the experience of someone who lives in a Black body.\" --Rev. angel Kyodo williams','inherit','closed','closed','','10788-autosave-v1','','','2016-10-13 03:08:44','2016-10-13 03:08:44','',10788,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10788-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10888,1,'2016-10-13 03:09:15','2016-10-13 03:09:15','As part of the 2016 Mindfulness Retreat for People of Color,  Rev. angel Kyodo williams offers a presentation and reading based on the newly published book, Radical Dharma.\r\n\r\nIn this, Rev. angel invites us into a long overdue conversation about race alongside love and liberation. As part of this conversation, Rev. angel speaks about the social construct of whiteness, while calling us back into our humanity and to be in touch with the \"thing underneath the thing.\"\r\n\r\n<strong>A few excerpts: </strong>\r\n<blockquote>\"...we have the greatest potential to actually pull it up at its roots. Interestingly enough, we have that opportunity through this gift of the Dharma that actually invites us to be able to look with clear seeing eyes at things that are not real...that are figments of our imagination and figments of other people\'s imaginations...Race is a grand social figment.\"\r\n\r\n\"As Dharma teachers, the way we survived the aggression and violence of a white dominant form of Dharma that was coming to us---is that we got underneath the thing. We got to the thing underneath the thing. We had to get down to who we really were. And simultaneously appreciate our teachers, our lineages, the texts as they were given but also have a fundamental trust in who we were in our basic humanity.\"\r\n\r\n\"What does Dharma become when it\'s expressed through the experience of someone who lives in a Black body.\" --Rev. angel Kyodo williams</blockquote>','Deer Park Dharmacast','\"What does Dharma become when it\'s expressed through the experience of someone who lives in a Black body.\" --Rev. angel Kyodo williams','inherit','closed','closed','','10788-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 03:09:15','2016-10-13 03:09:15','',10788,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10788-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10885,1,'2016-10-13 03:01:02','2016-10-13 03:01:02','\r\n2016 Mindfulness Retreat for People of Color. Dear Friends, We are happy to continue sharing the Dharma talks from The Path of True Love: Healing Ourselves, our recent mindfulness retreat for People of Color. Today, Rev. angel Kyodo williams offers a presentation and reading based on the newly published book, Radical Dharma.  In this sharing, Rev. angel invites us into a long overdue conversation about race alongside love and liberation.  As part of this conversation, Rev. angel speaks about the social construct of whiteness, while calling us back into our humanity and to be in touch with the \"thing underneath the thing.\" A few excerpts: \"...we have the greatest potential to actually pull it up at its roots.  Interestingly enough, we have that opportunity through this gift of the Dharma that actually invites us to be able to look with clear seeing eyes at things that are not real...that are figments of our imagination and figments of other people\'s imaginations...Race is a grand social figment.\"   \"As Dharma teachers, the way we survived the aggression and violence of a white dominant form of Dharma that was coming to us---is that we got underneath the thing. We got to the thing underneath the thing. We had to get down to who we really were. And simultaneously appreciate our teachers, our lineages, the texts as they were given but also have a fundamental trust in who we were in our basic humanity.\" \"What does Dharma become when it\'s expressed through the experience of someone who lives in a Black body.\" --Rev. angel Kyodo williams Let us now stop, listen deeply and contemplate these teachings and sharings to cultivate our individual and collective liberation and great aspiration to strengthen the Beloved Community. To stay connected with Rev. angel, visit angelkyodowilliams.com.','Deer Park Dharmacast','','inherit','closed','closed','','10788-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 03:01:02','2016-10-13 03:01:02','',10788,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10788-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10886,1,'2016-10-13 03:02:54','2016-10-13 03:02:54','','deerpark_dharmacast','','inherit','open','closed','','deerpark_dharmacast','','','2016-10-13 03:02:54','2016-10-13 03:02:54','',10788,'http://localhost/akyodo/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/deerpark_dharmacast.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(10887,1,'2016-10-13 03:03:00','2016-10-13 03:03:00','','buddhaboxes','','inherit','open','closed','','buddhaboxes','','','2016-10-13 03:03:00','2016-10-13 03:03:00','',10788,'http://localhost/akyodo/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/buddhaboxes.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(10893,1,'2016-10-13 03:42:05','2016-10-13 03:42:05','[audio mp3=\"\"][/audio]\n<h3></h3>\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"180\"]<a href=\"http://www.stitcher.com/s?fid=47138&amp;refid=stpr\"><img src=\"http://cloudfront.assets.stitcher.com/promo.assets/stitcher-banner-180x120.jpg\" alt=\"Listen to Stitcher\" width=\"180\" height=\"120\" /></a> Help us out: click to leave a review![/caption]\n<h3 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>angel Kyodo williams,</em> activist<em> and Zen Sensei, leads an engaging dialogue on race, Buddhism and social change with the New York City Buddhist community. Part one of a two part podcast.</em></h3>\n<blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>Meditation In The City</em> is the Shambhala Meditation Center of New York’s very own podcast! <a title=\"Meditation In the City Itunes\" href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/podcast/meditation-in-city-shambhala/id635143127\" target=\"_blank\">Subscribe to us on iTunes here.</a> Or <a title=\"Stitcher Radio\" href=\"http://www.stitcher.com/s?fid=47138&amp;refid=stpr\" target=\"_blank\">listen to us on Stitcher</a>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Get engaged with all your friends by telling them about the podcast!</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>Called “the most intriguing African-American Buddhist” by Library Journal, <strong>angel Kyodo williams</strong> is an author, activist and master trainer that has been bridging the worlds of spirit and justice since her critically acclaimed book, Being Black: Zen and the Art of Living With Fearlessness and Grace, signaled a shift in the perception of American Buddhism as all white and upper middle class. The book was hailed as “an act of love” by Pulitzer Prize winner Alice Walker, and “a classic” by Buddhist pioneer Jack Kornfield.</em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Currently one of only two black women Zen “Senseis” or teachers,  she applies wisdom teaching to social issues and is a leading voice for Transformative Social Change.  In recognition of her work, angel Sensei received the first Enlightened Society Award from Sakyong Mipham Rinpoche.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If you enjoy <em>Meditation in the City</em>, throw us a buck or two. Any amount will help support this podcast. It’s easy, just click the link below!</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a title=\"Pay Pal Podcast Donation\" href=\"https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_s-xclick&amp;hosted_button_id=UXBZU59T4Z4D2\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://ny.shambhala.org/files/2011/08/paypal-donate-button-copy.png\" alt=\"paypal-donate-button copy\" width=\"214\" height=\"99\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>Podcast production by <a title=\"Sonam Gray\" href=\"http://sonamgray.com/\" target=\"_blank\">sonamgray.com</a> and by David McKeel</em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Read the article here: <a href=\"http://ny.shambhala.org/2014/12/20/buddhist-call-action-part-1-podcast-episode-no-60/\" target=\"_blank\">http://ny.shambhala.org/2014/12/20/buddhist-call-action-part-1-podcast-episode-no-60/</a></p>','A Buddhist Call to Action (part 1) – Podcast Episode No. 60','','inherit','closed','closed','','10509-autosave-v1','','','2016-10-13 03:42:05','2016-10-13 03:42:05','',10509,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10509-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10894,1,'2016-10-13 03:43:01','2016-10-13 03:43:01','[audio mp3=\"\"][/audio]\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"180\"]<a href=\"http://www.stitcher.com/s?fid=47138&amp;refid=stpr\"><img src=\"http://cloudfront.assets.stitcher.com/promo.assets/stitcher-banner-180x120.jpg\" alt=\"Listen to Stitcher\" width=\"180\" height=\"120\" /></a> Help us out: click to leave a review![/caption]\r\n<h3 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>angel Kyodo williams,</em> activist<em> and Zen Sensei, leads an engaging dialogue on race, Buddhism and social change with the New York City Buddhist community. Part one of a two part podcast.</em></h3>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>Meditation In The City</em> is the Shambhala Meditation Center of New York’s very own podcast! <a title=\"Meditation In the City Itunes\" href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/podcast/meditation-in-city-shambhala/id635143127\" target=\"_blank\">Subscribe to us on iTunes here.</a> Or <a title=\"Stitcher Radio\" href=\"http://www.stitcher.com/s?fid=47138&amp;refid=stpr\" target=\"_blank\">listen to us on Stitcher</a>.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Get engaged with all your friends by telling them about the podcast!</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>Called “the most intriguing African-American Buddhist” by Library Journal, <strong>angel Kyodo williams</strong> is an author, activist and master trainer that has been bridging the worlds of spirit and justice since her critically acclaimed book, Being Black: Zen and the Art of Living With Fearlessness and Grace, signaled a shift in the perception of American Buddhism as all white and upper middle class. The book was hailed as “an act of love” by Pulitzer Prize winner Alice Walker, and “a classic” by Buddhist pioneer Jack Kornfield.</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Currently one of only two black women Zen “Senseis” or teachers,  she applies wisdom teaching to social issues and is a leading voice for Transformative Social Change.  In recognition of her work, angel Sensei received the first Enlightened Society Award from Sakyong Mipham Rinpoche.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If you enjoy <em>Meditation in the City</em>, throw us a buck or two. Any amount will help support this podcast. It’s easy, just click the link below!</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a title=\"Pay Pal Podcast Donation\" href=\"https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_s-xclick&amp;hosted_button_id=UXBZU59T4Z4D2\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://ny.shambhala.org/files/2011/08/paypal-donate-button-copy.png\" alt=\"paypal-donate-button copy\" width=\"214\" height=\"99\" /></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><em>Podcast production by <a title=\"Sonam Gray\" href=\"http://sonamgray.com/\" target=\"_blank\">sonamgray.com</a> and by David McKeel</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Read the article here: <a href=\"http://ny.shambhala.org/2014/12/20/buddhist-call-action-part-1-podcast-episode-no-60/\" target=\"_blank\">http://ny.shambhala.org/2014/12/20/buddhist-call-action-part-1-podcast-episode-no-60/</a></p>','A Buddhist Call to Action (part 1) – Podcast Episode No. 60','angel Kyodo williams, activist and Zen Sensei, leads an engaging dialogue on race, Buddhism and social change with the New York City Buddhist community. Part one of a two part podcast.','inherit','closed','closed','','10509-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 03:43:01','2016-10-13 03:43:01','',10509,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10509-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10895,1,'2016-10-13 03:43:29','2016-10-13 03:43:29','[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"180\"]<a href=\"http://www.stitcher.com/s?fid=47138&amp;refid=stpr\"><img style=\"margin-top: 12%;\" src=\"http://cloudfront.assets.stitcher.com/promo.assets/stitcher-banner-180x120.jpg\" alt=\"Listen to Stitcher\" width=\"180\" height=\"120\" /></a> Help us out: click to leave a review![/caption]\r\n<h3 style=\"text-align: justify;\"></h3>\r\n<h3 style=\"text-align: justify;\">angel Kyodo williams, activist and Zen Sensei, leads an engaging dialogue on race, Buddhism and social change with the New York City Buddhist community. Part two of a two part podcast. Listen to part one <a href=\"http://ny.shambhala.org/2014/12/20/buddhist-call-action-part-1-podcast-episode-no-60/\">here</a>.</h3>\r\nMeditation In The City is the Shambhala Meditation Center of New York’s very own podcast! <a title=\"Meditation In the City Itunes\" href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/podcast/meditation-in-city-shambhala/id635143127\" target=\"_blank\">Subscribe to us on iTunes here.</a> Or <a title=\"Stitcher Radio\" href=\"http://www.stitcher.com/s?fid=47138&amp;refid=stpr\" target=\"_blank\">listen to us on Stitcher</a>.\r\n\r\nGet engaged with all your friends by telling them about the podcast!\r\n\r\nCalled “the most intriguing African-American Buddhist” by Library Journal, angel Kyodo williams is an author, activist and master trainer that has been bridging the worlds of spirit and justice since her critically acclaimed book, Being Black: Zen and the Art of Living With Fearlessness and Grace, signaled a shift in the perception of American Buddhism as all white and upper middle class. The book was hailed as “an act of love” by Pulitzer Prize winner Alice Walker, and “a classic” by Buddhist pioneer Jack Kornfield.\r\n\r\nCurrently one of only two black women Zen “Senseis” or teachers,  she applies wisdom teaching to social issues and is a leading voice for Transformative Social Change.  In recognition of her work, angel Sensei received the first Enlightened Society Award from Sakyong Mipham Rinpoche.\r\n\r\nIf you enjoy Meditation in the City, throw us a buck or two. Any amount will help support this podcast. It’s easy, just click the link below!\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Pay Pal Podcast Donation\" href=\"https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_s-xclick&amp;hosted_button_id=UXBZU59T4Z4D2\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://ny.shambhala.org/files/2011/08/paypal-donate-button-copy.png\" alt=\"paypal-donate-button copy\" width=\"214\" height=\"99\" /></a>\r\n\r\nPodcast production by <a title=\"Sonam Gray\" href=\"http://sonamgray.com/\" target=\"_blank\">sonamgray.com</a> and by David McKeel\r\n\r\nRead the article here: <a href=\"http://ny.shambhala.org/2015/01/02/buddhist-call-action-part-2-podcast-episode-no-61/\" target=\"_blank\">http://ny.shambhala.org/2015/01/02/buddhist-call-action-part-2-podcast-episode-no-61/</a>','A Buddhist Call to Action (part 2) – Podcast Episode No. 61','angel Kyodo williams, activist and Zen Sensei, leads an engaging dialogue on race, Buddhism and social change with the New York City Buddhist community. Part two of a two part podcast.','inherit','closed','closed','','10602-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 03:43:29','2016-10-13 03:43:29','',10602,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10602-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10896,1,'2016-10-13 04:29:29','2016-10-13 04:29:29','Zen teacher and social activist angel Kyodo williams reminds us that societies can change on a massive scale. At one time, slavery was considered an economic necessity, but new ways were found because society could no longer bear it. Angel asks, can todays society reject individualism on that scale?','Global Oneness Project: angel Kyodo williams Interview','','inherit','closed','closed','','10287-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 04:29:29','2016-10-13 04:29:29','',10287,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10287-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10899,1,'2016-10-13 05:35:35','2016-10-13 05:35:35','Zen teacher and social activist angel Kyodo williams reminds us that societies can change on a massive scale. At one time, slavery was considered an economic necessity, but new ways were found because society could no longer bear it. Angel asks, can todays society reject individualism on that scale?\r\n','Global Oneness Project: angel Kyodo williams Interview','','inherit','closed','closed','','10287-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 05:35:35','2016-10-13 05:35:35','',10287,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10287-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10897,1,'2016-10-13 05:29:58','2016-10-13 05:29:58','Zen teacher and social activist angel Kyodo williams reminds us that societies can change on a massive scale. At one time, slavery was considered an economic necessity, but new ways were found because society could no longer bear it. Angel asks, can todays society reject individualism on that scale?\r\n\r\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DqcyRNezssU','Global Oneness Project: angel Kyodo williams Interview','','inherit','closed','closed','','10287-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 05:29:58','2016-10-13 05:29:58','',10287,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10287-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10898,1,'2016-10-13 05:29:59','2016-10-13 05:29:59','','Global Oneness Project: angel Kyodo williams Interview','','inherit','open','closed','','global-oneness-project-angel-kyodo-williams-interview','','','2016-10-13 05:29:59','2016-10-13 05:29:59','',10287,'http://localhost/akyodo/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/global-oneness-project-angel-kyodo-williams-interview.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(10900,1,'2016-10-13 05:58:19','2016-10-13 05:58:19','Zen teacher and social activist angel Kyodo williams reminds us that societies can change on a massive scale. At one time, slavery was considered an economic necessity, but new ways were found because society could no longer bear it. Angel asks, can todays society reject individualism on that scale?\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DqcyRNezssU','Global Oneness Project: angel Kyodo williams Interview','','inherit','closed','closed','','10287-autosave-v1','','','2016-10-13 05:58:19','2016-10-13 05:58:19','',10287,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10287-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10901,1,'2016-10-13 06:01:28','2016-10-13 06:01:28','angel leads a meditation joining an ancient instruction w/ modern centering.\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jk9SHiDcH1o\n[embed]https://youtu.be/jk9SHiDcH1o[/embed]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>4-Line Sit  &amp; Centering Instruction</strong>\n\n1. Sit Upright\n2. Ears against the shoulders\n3. Nose against the navel\n4. Give one FULL outbreath\n\n#WEmeditate #MindfulMondays\n\nJoin CTZNWELL for more FREE live Mindful Monday meditations by registering at <a class=\"yt-uix-redirect-link\" title=\"http://www.ctznwell.org/practice\" href=\"http://www.ctznwell.org/practice\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.ctznwell.org/practice</a>','Mindful Mondays - Week 1','','inherit','closed','closed','','9966-autosave-v1','','','2016-10-13 06:01:28','2016-10-13 06:01:28','',9966,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/9966-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10902,1,'2016-10-13 06:22:03','2016-10-13 06:22:03','Rev. angel Kyodo williams explores what lineage can oﬀer us and what it takes away. She has been graced with the honor of soon becoming only the second Black woman recognized as a teacher in the Zen tradition. Lineage—its keeping and its transcending—is on her mind.\r\nLINK: <a href=\"https://brooklynzen.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Brooklyn Zen Center</a>','&quot;Lineage: Touching the Earth, Making Room for Everyone&quot; - Brooklyn Zen Center','Rev. angel Kyodo williams explores what lineage can oﬀer us and what it takes away. She has been graced with the honor of soon becoming only the second Black woman recognized as a teacher in the Zen tradition. Lineage—its keeping and its transcending—is on her mind.','inherit','closed','closed','','10640-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 06:22:03','2016-10-13 06:22:03','',10640,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10640-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10903,1,'2016-10-13 06:24:15','2016-10-13 06:24:15','LINK: <a href=\"http://www.rockblossom.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Rock Blossom Sangha: Brooklyn Community of Mindfulness</a>','&quot;love and justice are not two: diversity & inclusion in sanghas&quot; - Rock Blossom Sangha','','inherit','closed','closed','','10638-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 06:24:15','2016-10-13 06:24:15','',10638,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10638-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10904,1,'2016-10-13 06:27:12','2016-10-13 06:27:12','LINK: <a href=\"https://brooklynzen.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Brooklyn Zen Center</a>','&quot;buddha meets buddha: love and justice are not two&quot; - Brooklyn Zen Center','','inherit','closed','closed','','10636-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 06:27:12','2016-10-13 06:27:12','',10636,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10636-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10905,1,'2016-10-13 06:30:41','2016-10-13 06:30:41','LINK: <a href=\"https://brooklynzen.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Brooklyn Zen Center</a>','&quot;buddha meets buddha: love and justice are not two&quot; - Brooklyn Zen Center','&nbsp;','inherit','closed','closed','','10636-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 06:30:41','2016-10-13 06:30:41','',10636,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10636-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10906,1,'2016-10-13 06:31:48','2016-10-13 06:31:48','LINK: <a href=\"http://www.rockblossom.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Rock Blossom Sangha: Brooklyn Community of Mindfulness</a>','&quot;love and justice are not two: diversity & inclusion in sanghas&quot; - Rock Blossom Sangha','&nbsp;','inherit','closed','closed','','10638-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 06:31:48','2016-10-13 06:31:48','',10638,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10638-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10907,1,'2016-10-13 06:45:11','2016-10-13 06:45:11','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vqHQuVnPGEk\n\nReverend angel Kyodo williams speaks with campaign and citizen activists from the Stand community and beyond on how activists can use Radical Dharma to confront white supremacy and privilege. The racial violence of the weeks preceding the seminar drove home the urgency of the topic for the 170 participants.\n\nRev. angel presented on Radical Dharma and Activism: Confronting Inequity in Our Own Work for Social Change, exploring how we can use mindfulness to confront white supremacy and white privilege in our lives and our work. Stand executive director Todd Paglia introduced Rev. angel. After Rev. angel’s opening remarks, Todd asked Rev. angel an initial set of questions and then brought in questions from the audience.\n\nThe webinar included discussions on why using the phrase white supremacy is critical, why it’s important to see differences between people even while acknowledging that we are all one, why a mindfulness approach helps people confront inequity, and how each person needs to learn to love and free their own self on the way to promoting love and freedom for everyone else.\n\nLINK: <a href=\"http://www.stand.earth/\" target=\"_blank\">Stand</a>','Radical Dharma and Activism: Confronting Inequity in Our Own Work for Social Change - sponsored by Stand','','inherit','closed','closed','','10624-autosave-v1','','','2016-10-13 06:45:11','2016-10-13 06:45:11','',10624,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10624-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10908,1,'2016-10-13 06:45:33','2016-10-13 06:45:33','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vqHQuVnPGEk\r\n\r\nReverend angel Kyodo williams speaks with campaign and citizen activists from the Stand community and beyond on how activists can use Radical Dharma to confront white supremacy and privilege. The racial violence of the weeks preceding the seminar drove home the urgency of the topic for the 170 participants.\r\n\r\nRev. angel presented on Radical Dharma and Activism: Confronting Inequity in Our Own Work for Social Change, exploring how we can use mindfulness to confront white supremacy and white privilege in our lives and our work. Stand executive director Todd Paglia introduced Rev. angel. After Rev. angel’s opening remarks, Todd asked Rev. angel an initial set of questions and then brought in questions from the audience.\r\n\r\nThe webinar included discussions on why using the phrase white supremacy is critical, why it’s important to see differences between people even while acknowledging that we are all one, why a mindfulness approach helps people confront inequity, and how each person needs to learn to love and free their own self on the way to promoting love and freedom for everyone else.\r\n\r\nLINK: <a href=\"http://www.stand.earth/\" target=\"_blank\">Stand</a>','Radical Dharma and Activism: Confronting Inequity in Our Own Work for Social Change - sponsored by Stand','','inherit','closed','closed','','10624-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 06:45:33','2016-10-13 06:45:33','',10624,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10624-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10909,1,'2016-10-13 06:45:35','2016-10-13 06:45:35','','Radical Dharma and Activism: Confronting Inequity in Our Own Work for Social Change &#8211; sponsored by Stand','','inherit','open','closed','','radical-dharma-and-activism-confronting-inequity-in-our-own-work-for-social-change-sponsored-by-stand-2','','','2016-10-13 06:45:35','2016-10-13 06:45:35','',10624,'http://localhost/akyodo/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/radical-dharma-and-activism-confronting-inequity-in-our-own-work-for-social-change-8211-sponsored-by-stand.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(10910,1,'2016-10-13 06:50:50','2016-10-13 06:50:50','','our-duty-to-win_sm-bw','','inherit','open','closed','','our-duty-to-win_sm-bw','','','2016-10-13 06:50:50','2016-10-13 06:50:50','',10624,'http://localhost/akyodo/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/our-duty-to-win_sm-bw.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(10911,1,'2016-10-13 06:54:40','2016-10-13 06:54:40','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DqcyRNezssU\r\n\r\nZen teacher and social activist angel Kyodo williams reminds us that societies can change on a massive scale. At one time, slavery was considered an economic necessity, but new ways were found because society could no longer bear it. Angel asks, can today\'s society reject individualism on that scale?','Global Oneness Project: angel Kyodo williams Interview','Zen teacher and social activist angel Kyodo williams reminds us that societies can change on a massive scale. At one time, slavery was considered an economic necessity, but new ways were found because society could no longer bear it. Angel asks, can today\'s society reject individualism on that scale?','inherit','closed','closed','','10287-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 06:54:40','2016-10-13 06:54:40','',10287,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10287-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10912,1,'2016-10-13 06:54:41','2016-10-13 06:54:41','','Global Oneness Project: angel Kyodo williams Interview','','inherit','open','closed','','global-oneness-project-angel-kyodo-williams-interview-2','','','2016-10-13 06:54:41','2016-10-13 06:54:41','',10287,'http://localhost/akyodo/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/global-oneness-project-angel-kyodo-williams-interview-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(10913,1,'2016-10-13 06:55:32','2016-10-13 06:55:32','Lama Rod Owens and angel Kyodo williams discuss the challenges of being teachers of color in predominantly white communities. Read their conversation in the Winter 2014 issue of Buddhadharma.','Rod Owens and angel Kyodo williams in Dialogue','Lama Rod Owens and angel Kyodo williams discuss the challenges of being teachers of color in predominantly white communities. Read their conversation in the Winter 2014 issue of Buddhadharma.','inherit','closed','closed','','10285-autosave-v1','','','2016-10-13 06:55:32','2016-10-13 06:55:32','',10285,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10285-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10914,1,'2016-10-13 06:56:21','2016-10-13 06:56:21','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RX9vAEHShZs\r\n\r\nLama Rod Owens and angel Kyodo williams discuss the challenges of being teachers of color in predominantly white communities. Read their conversation in the Winter 2014 issue of Buddhadharma.','Rod Owens and angel Kyodo williams in Dialogue','Lama Rod Owens and angel Kyodo williams discuss the challenges of being teachers of color in predominantly white communities. Read their conversation in the Winter 2014 issue of Buddhadharma.','inherit','closed','closed','','10285-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 06:56:21','2016-10-13 06:56:21','',10285,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/10285-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10915,1,'2016-10-13 06:58:51','2016-10-13 06:58:51','','Rod Owens and angel Kyodo williams in Dialogue','','inherit','open','closed','','rod-owens-and-angel-kyodo-williams-in-dialogue-2','','','2016-10-13 06:58:51','2016-10-13 06:58:51','',10285,'http://localhost/akyodo/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/rod-owens-and-angel-kyodo-williams-in-dialogue.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(10916,1,'2016-10-13 07:01:41','2016-10-13 07:01:41','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Fd8luWXIrrc\nangel Kyodo williams speaks on climate change, connecting the roots of climate change to racial justice and an economic system that demands the degradation of human beings and the planet.\n\nThis talk was delivered on May 14, 2015 for the first official invitation from the White House to the Buddhist Community.  The gathering and White House visit and briefing included more than 80 Buddhist leaders and teachers engaged in social change.\n\n','An Inconvenient Dharma: Cutting the Roots of Climate Change','angel Kyodo williams speaks on climate change, connecting the roots of climate change to racial justice and an economic system that demands the degradation of human beings and the planet.','inherit','closed','closed','','9972-autosave-v1','','','2016-10-13 07:01:41','2016-10-13 07:01:41','',9972,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/9972-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10917,1,'2016-10-13 07:01:43','2016-10-13 07:01:43','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Fd8luWXIrrc\r\nangel Kyodo williams speaks on climate change, connecting the roots of climate change to racial justice and an economic system that demands the degradation of human beings and the planet.\r\n\r\nThis talk was delivered on May 14, 2015 for the first official invitation from the White House to the Buddhist Community.  The gathering and White House visit and briefing included more than 80 Buddhist leaders and teachers engaged in social change.\r\n\r\n','An Inconvenient Dharma: Cutting the Roots of Climate Change','angel Kyodo williams speaks on climate change, connecting the roots of climate change to racial justice and an economic system that demands the degradation of human beings and the planet.','inherit','closed','closed','','9972-revision-v1','','','2016-10-13 07:01:43','2016-10-13 07:01:43','',9972,'http://localhost/akyodo/blog/2016/10/13/9972-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10918,1,'2016-10-13 07:01:44','2016-10-13 07:01:44','','An Inconvenient Dharma: Cutting the Roots of Climate Change','','inherit','open','closed','','an-inconvenient-dharma-cutting-the-roots-of-climate-change-2','','','2016-10-13 07:01:44','2016-10-13 07:01:44','',9972,'http://localhost/akyodo/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/an-inconvenient-dharma-cutting-the-roots-of-climate-change.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(10919,1,'2016-10-13 07:03:46','2016-10-13 07:03:46','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jk9SHiDcH1o\r\n\r\nangel leads a meditation joining an ancient instruction w/ modern centering.\r\n\r\n<strong>4-Line Sit  &amp; Centering Instruction</strong>\r\n\r\n1. Sit Upright\r\n2. Ears against the shoulders\r\n3. Nose against the navel\r\n4. Give one FULL outbreath\r\n\r\n#WEmeditate #MindfulMondays\r\n\r\nJoin CTZNWELL for more FREE live Mindful Monday meditations by registering at <a class=\"yt-uix-redirect-link\" title=\"http://www.ctznwell.org/practice\" href=\"http://www.ctznwell.org/practice\" targ